title Cloud sandbox toolchain raised; Neth witnesses run real GREEN, not just by inspection
prompt Keaton asked to get this cloud environment set up, or look for previous iOS instructions, and to compose documentation from what was found.
think searched the tree for prior Cursor-for-iOS or cloud-session tooling before guessing at a fresh approach -- found external-research/20260708-211637_ios-session-claude-review-brief.md naming that an earlier iOS round ran parity.rish GREEN on a cloud bench, which meant a working toolchain-raise recipe already existed somewhere rather than needing to be invented from nothing.
think grepped for the actual fetch mechanic behind that claim and found it in work-in-progress/20260703-021412_counsel-and-confirmation-tests.md's Step 1 -- pip install ziglang==0.16.0, symlinked into vendor/zig-toolchain, RYE_ZIG exported, then rye/bootstrap.sh and a rishi build. That earlier round used it inside a persistent ai-jail host; the question worth answering honestly was whether the same recipe raises cleanly on a genuinely disposable Cursor Cloud Agent VM, which is a different kind of host than either the macOS or Ubuntu-desktop paths already documented.
think ran the exact recipe end to end on this host: pip install succeeded (98MB wheel), the symlink needed vendor/ created first (mkdir -p, the template docs assume it already exists on a host that has run this before), rye/bootstrap.sh printed its version line cleanly, and the rishi build succeeded on the first try -- no language gaps or bugs hit this time, unlike several prior macOS-host sessions that found real Rish/Rye bugs along the way.
think rather than trusting the raise merely completed without error, ran all three living Neth witnesses (root, serial-core, and the two-posture install landed this same session) and confirmed each printed its own real GREEN line -- this is the first time any Neth witness has run outside a Mac-hosted or Ubuntu-desktop sitting, and the first time the two-posture root install specifically has been proven rather than merely reasoned about by inspection.
think named the one real trade-off honestly in the new guide rather than presenting pip's ziglang package as equivalent to the checksum-verified official fetch rye/README.md documents for a persistent host: it is a different, real trust chain (PyPI + the ziglang maintainer's repackaging), acceptable for a same-sitting disposable VM, not a silent substitute for the verified path on a host that keeps its identity and tooling for weeks.
think also named plainly why ai-jail itself has nothing to add on this kind of host -- the whole point of ai-jail and --private-home is carving a boundary out of a shared, persistent machine; a fresh Cursor Cloud Agent VM already starts as that boundary, so building jail tooling here would be solving an already-solved problem rather than a real gap.
think checked whether the full parity.rish sequential suite could run further here than it does on macOS (Wayland being Linux-native, unlike on the Mac) -- found libwayland-dev/libxkbcommon-dev are not installed on this minimal cloud image either, so the same named gap holds here for a different underlying reason; did not attempt to close it this session, named it as a real, separate future pass instead of quietly working around it.
obs this closes an open honesty gap from the very session that landed the root-install code: that session correctly named "not yet run GREEN, no toolchain in this cloud environment" as a real limitation rather than a false claim -- this session found that the limitation was closeable in the same kind of environment, not a permanent one, and closed it.
obs per the standing instruction to flag dependency installs likely needed by future cloud agents: pip install ziglang==0.16.0 pulled a real ~98MB wheel into this session's own sandbox. If cloud-hosted witness runs against this repository's rye/rishi toolchain become a standing need rather than an occasional one, baking this raise into the environment's own base image (via an env-setup agent at cursor.com/onboard) would save every future session repeating the same four-command raise -- named in the new guide as a possibility, not acted on unprompted this session.
file manual/guides/cloud-agent-toolchain-setup.md -- new; the confirmed recipe, the honest trust-chain trade-off, what it deliberately does not set up (no ai-jail, no Wayland, no persistence)
file work-in-progress/TASKS.md -- Neth two-posture root install item updated from "not yet run GREEN" to "confirmed GREEN on a raised cloud sandbox"; new item naming the cloud-agent toolchain raise itself as landed
file session-logs/20260715-062000_cloud-toolchain-raised-neth-green.bron -- this log
recommend keep-going -- the recipe is real, confirmed, and honestly limited (no Wayland headers, no persistence across sessions, a named different trust chain from the checksum-verified path). The next Neth lap in order, per the ladder in TASKS.md, is apply-step crash safety -- root application as a step distinct from root writing, witnessed by a crash-in-the-window test -- and this cloud sandbox can now build and run that witness directly, the same session it is written, rather than waiting on an outside host.
